	<ul class='nav-list'>
				<li><a href='#'>2011</a></li>
				
				<li><a href='#'>2018</a></li>
				
				<li><a href='#'>2023</a></li>
				
	</ul>
<p><span class="wp-caption-text">Satellite images show how a large portion of Nyangai has been subsumed by the sea. Images by Google Earth</span></p>
<p>“The water is eating the island,” says Tewoh Koroma, a mother of six who lost her home to flooding in September 2023. “We already fled from the water once and now we’re getting flooded again. The water is following us.”</p>
<p>Over the past decade, each new storm or flood has prompted more to leave. Some head for the country’s coastal capital, Freetown, or to other towns on the mainland, while others move to nearby islands. Nyangai’s leaders say there were once more than 500 homes here. Today there are fewer than 100.</p>
<p>The Turtle Islands archipelago, in which Nyangai lies, has always been vulnerable to erosion. Most of the islands rise little more than a meter or two above sea level, and their loose soils are easily shifted by the ocean’s powerful currents. Stretches of shoreline slowly recede or advance, and offshore sandbanks come and go. But the crisis now unfolding on Nyangai is on a different scale. Since 2014, the island has shrunk from roughly 700 meters long to just 170. Many blame the increasingly erratic weather and more powerful storms. As one resident puts it, “Everything’s out of place.”</p>
<div id="attachment_45077" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai.jpg"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-45077 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="An aerial view shows the remnants of Nyangai Island, Sierra Leone." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/1-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">An aerial view shows the remnants of Nyangai Island, Sierra Leone.</p></div>
<p>Life on Nyangai has never been easy. The island lacks roads, piped water, and electricity. Living conditions are basic. But it’s only with deep reluctance that many finally leave. The island is peaceful, its community tight-knit. It’s free of snakes and has virtually no malaria. The fishing, on which nearly everyone relies, is better than elsewhere. During times of upheaval, from Sierra Leone’s civil war in the 1990s to the Ebola outbreak of 2014, the island has offered a level of sanctuary. For most, it is the only home they have ever known.</p>
<p>Nyangai is not alone in its existential battle with the ocean; similar scenes are unfolding along much of Sierra Leone’s coastline. In the village of Lakka, near Freetown, the ocean is washing away two-story concrete houses piece by piece. On Plantain Island, some 30 kilometers to the north of Nyangai, farmers have seen their agricultural land either contaminated with salt water or swept away altogether. And in the north of the country, residents of the bustling trading town on Yelibuya Island have found themselves forced to retreat ever farther inland to escape the encroaching sea.</p>
<div id="attachment_45079" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai.jpg"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-45079 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-1200x801.jpg" alt="aerial photo of Nyangai Island in 2014" width="1200" height="801" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-1200x801.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-768x513.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-2048x1367.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/3-nyangai-900x601.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">This aerial view shows Nyangai Island in December 2014, shortly before the sea split it into two.</p></div>
<p>“It’s becoming very alarming,” says Tamba Emmanuel Nyaka, the deputy director of the Climate Change Secretariat in Sierra Leone’s Environment Protection Agency, who recently visited some of the worst affected areas. “We realize that the problem is getting worse. People showed us where they used to live, where their cemetery was, their fields, houses, and now it’s just seawater. They’re constantly having to move.”</p>
<p>Government officials say natural processes are being exacerbated by a series of factors including changing weather patterns, rising sea levels, the felling of mangrove forests, and in more urban areas, the mining of beach sand for construction. In 2021, the government released a new <a href="https://faolex.fao.org/docs/pdf/sie214108.pdf">National Adaptation Plan</a> to address the impacts of climate change, but it’s hamstrung by both a lack of data—the country’s first marine meteorological station has been operating for only two years—and a lack of resources. The government has implemented mangrove restoration projects in some areas but with limited success. As for Nyangai, an official confirmed there are no plans to build any sea defenses.</p>
<div id="attachment_45078" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45078 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-1200x900.jpg" alt="aerial photo of Nyangai Island" width="1200" height="900" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-520x390.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-768x576.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-900x675.jpg 900w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2-nyangai-1024x768.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Island elders say that Nyangai once held three villages, large areas of forest, and a thriving community.</p></div>
<p>Almost everyone still on Nyangai has lost at least one home in recent years, and some, like 35-year-old Gaya Bang, have lost as many as four. “We’ve spent so much money building new houses,” she says.</p>
<p>With so much uncertainty over the island’s future, most people now rebuild with only basic materials: squares of sackcloth over a grid of sticks for walls; old metal sheets, often riddled with holes, for roofs. Gone are the neat mud-walled cottages I had seen on my first visit. Gone too is the island’s freshwater supply; the well water is now so brackish it can be used only for washing. In the rainy season, islanders collect rainwater in buckets. In the dry season, they must take an hour-and-a-half round trip by boat to collect water from neighboring islands.</p>
<p>The atmosphere, too, has changed. Children still entertain themselves, devising games in the tree graveyards that ring parts of the island, but the electric energy of a busy fishing village has given way to a sense of lethargy. The island’s chief laments that the parties and cultural dances that used to be common have faded away. These days, he says, the sound system comes out just once or twice a year to mark the rare visits by campaigning politicians.</p>
<div id="attachment_45080" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45080 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Children look out to sea from the stumps of palm trees." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/4-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Children look out to sea from the stumps of palm trees.</p></div>
<p>“We’ve been telling the government … that we need help,” says Hasan Kargbo, the island’s harbor master. “But so far we’ve seen nothing.”</p>
<p>Seeing little prospect of outside intervention, the islanders attempted to stem the erosion by planting mangroves, but few of the seedlings survived for long. When the island floods during the highest tides, some build levees of sand around their homes, bolstered with sheets of tarpaulin, lengths of timber, car tires, or any other sturdy objects they find lying around. Beyond that, there’s little they can do but wait for the tide to go down.</p>
<p>“We love our island,” says Kargbo, who has already started looking for a piece of land on the mainland to start a new life with his wife and six children. “[But] it’s going to disappear.”</p>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45081" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45081 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="A woman carries a bucket of water through the cramped maze of shacks huddled on the last inhabitable area of the island. " width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/5-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A woman carries a bucket of water through the cramped maze of shacks huddled on the last inhabitable area of the island.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45082" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45082 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Dead and dying trees, the remnants of what elders say was once a forest, dot the fast-receding shoreline of Nyangai Island." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/6-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Dead and dying trees, the remnants of what elders say was once a forest, dot the fast-receding shoreline of Nyangai Island.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45083" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45083 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Hasan Kargbo, 32, photographed at his home, is searching for a place to relocate his family." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/7-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Hasan Kargbo, 32, photographed at his home, is searching for a place to relocate his family.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45084" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45084 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Gaya Bang prepares a meal by torchlight in the early morning. Her family has lost four homes to the sea. " width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/8-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Gaya Bang prepares a meal by torchlight in the early morning. Her family has lost four homes to the sea.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45085" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45085 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Fishermen prepare their nets while a rising tide approaches nearby homes." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/9-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Fishermen prepare their nets while a rising tide approaches nearby homes.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45086" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45086 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Eight-year-old Ndole Kamara perches on the side of his family’s fish-smoking hut as the rising tide laps against its walls. " width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/10-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Eight-year-old Ndole Kamara perches on the side of his family’s fish-smoking hut as the rising tide laps against its walls.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45087" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45087 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="A chicken prepares to jump off a stump surrounded by flood waters." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/11-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A chicken prepares to jump off a stump surrounded by floodwaters.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45088" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45088 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="A resident rushes to build a sand barrier in an attempt to protect her home from high-tide flooding. " width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/12-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A resident rushes to build a sand barrier in an attempt to protect her home from high-tide flooding.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45089" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45089 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="A boy looks on as seawater floods into his home." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/13-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A boy looks on as seawater floods into his home.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45090" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45090 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="Children wade through floodwater. Several thousand people once lived on Nyangai Island. Now, all but around 400 have fled." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/14-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Children wade through floodwater. Several thousand people once lived on Nyangai Island. Now, all but around 400 have fled.</p></div>
<hr />
<div id="attachment_45091" class="wp-caption alignnone" ><a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45091 size-large" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-1200x800.jpg" alt="A boy climbs on a fallen tree killed by seawater." width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-520x347.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-768x512.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/15-nyangai-900x600.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A boy climbs on a fallen tree killed by seawater.</p></div>
